<DOC><DOCNO> AP890223-0104 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1144EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0519 02-23 0803</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0519,0820</SECOND><HEAD>Arctic Air, Snow Covers Much of East; Snow Hits South</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with record lows, snow acrossSouth, storm expected tonight, picks up 5th graf, ``A heavy ...'</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Bitterly cold air rushed across the Deep South today, with snowfalling almost as far south as the Gulf of Mexico, and heavy snowfell around Chicago.   Temperatures crashed to record lows across the Midwest and as farsouth as Tennessee, and wind chill factors fell below zero deep inthe South. Pensacola, Fla., fell to 30 degrees.   Snow flurries were reported in Alabama as far south as northernMobile and Baldwin counties on the Gulf coast. The snow accumulatedin northern Alabama and state authorities said Interstate 59 northof Trussville and Interstate 20 near Leeds were closed.   An inch of snow fell at Athens, Ga., with flurries across Georgiato the Florida border, and visibility was as low as one mile in snowat Meridian, Miss.   Record lows today included 17 at Memphis, Tenn.; 2 at KansasCity, Mo.; 13 below zero at Norfolk, Neb.; 13 below zero at Spencer,Iowa; and 10 below zero at Traverse City, Mich.   A combination of cold and gusty wind produced wind chill valuesof 11 degrees below zero at Memphis Naval Air Station in Tennessee,14 below at Harrison, Ark., and 22 below at Springfield, Mo.   The National Weather Service said temperatures tonight would fallto the teens in Alabama from Huntsville to Mobile, and said manyefforts to save crops would be fruitless because of strong wind andthe duration of freezing temperatures.   Schools were closed in sections of Tennessee, South Carolina andGeorgia, including the University of Georgia. One Georgia trafficdeath was blamed on icy pavement.   A low pressure system was expected to develop off the Carolinacoast tonight and spread snow from North Carolina across easternsections of the mid Atlantic states toward southern New England, theweather service said. Winter storm watches were posted from NorthCarolina up the coast to New York City.   Snow also fell around the Great Lakes, with the heaviestaccumulations around the southern tip of Lake Michigan.   Porter County in extreme northwest Indiana reported 13 inches ofsnow and 6 to 10 inches were reported in Lake County, Ill., justnorth of Chicago. High winds caused near blizzard conditions in someareas.   A heavy snow warning was in effect for portions of northwestIndiana and northeast Illinois.   Snow advisories were in effect for northeast Alabama, easternTennessee, the northern mountains of North Carolina, portions ofOhio, and along Lake Ontario in western New York state.   Temperatures along the East Coast were dropping, reflecting theforward edge of the arctic air, but readings were still abovefreezing as far north as southern New England.   Early morning temperatures were mild in the West, with readingsin the 30s and 40s in most places, 50s in California, and 50s to mid60s in the Desert Southwest.   Showers were widely scattered over the northwest quarter of thenation.   Today's forecast called for light snow over much of the East fromNew England to northern Georgia and into the Appalachians. Rain wasexpected directly along the coast. Rain also was forecast for thePacific Northwest, and rain or snow was predicted for the northernPlateau and northern Rockies.   Highs were expected to be in the single digits and teens over theGreat Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley; the 20s and 30s overmost of the eastern half of the nation, with lower 40s along theCarolina coast; the 40s to lower 60s over central and southernFlorida; and the 40s and 50s in most of the nation from the Plainsto the Pacific Coast, with 60s in southwest Texas, New Mexico andmuch of California, and 70s to mid 80s in Southern California andthe Desert Southwest.   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 17 degrees below zero atHibbing, Minn., and Sioux Falls, S.D., to 67 degrees at Key West,Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 27 fair; Boston 37 cloudy; Buffalo 18 snow;Charleston, S.C. 42 cloudy; Cincinnati 17 partly cloudy; Cleveland17 snow; Detroit 7 fair; Miami 58 fair; New York 36 windy;Philadelphia 35 fair; Pittsburgh 19 snow; Portland, Maine 32 cloudy;Washington 38 cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck 7 fair; Chicago 11 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 28fair; Denver 30 cloudy; Des Moines -5 fair; Indianapolis 12 fair;Kansas City 5 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul -8 fair; Nashville 20 snow;New Orleans 38 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 40 fair; Anchorage 19 fair; Las Vegas 50partly cloudy; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 57 fair; San Diego 58fair; San Francisco 49 fair; Seattle 43 partly cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 14 fair; Toronto 7 windy.</TEXT></DOC>